VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'history and might not repeat itself, but it does rhyme. A lot of the tactics you recognize from SEO are applicable in GEO with some important nuances. So to start with some simple'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'definitions, GEO stands for generative engine optimization. And those generative engines are the AI models that I was referring to earlier. So think of them like Google\'s Gemini.'

[05:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Gemini reaches 2 billion people every single week. They see the answers generated by Gemini in Google\'s AI overviews, inside the Gemini app, and'

[05:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'across a host of different surfaces. So think of that as one generative engine with reach far beyond only a handful of platforms could even rival it. So, in'

[05:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that case, Geo is generative engine. And then the optimization question becomes really interesting because those generative engines and Gemini\'s by far the most influential followed by and'

[06:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI\'s ChatGPT, Anthropic\'s Claude, Perplexity, Deep Seek, or Meta AI. Those models have learned about a category, a brand, and a product largely'

[06:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through their training data. And that\'s often what we refer to when we think about a knowledge cut-off. You know, billions of different data points from text, image, audio, and video that'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'eventually help that model think about the world. You can optimize your content to try and stand out in that training set. Or you can optimize to be one of the first'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'topical and timely sources those models find when they look beyond their training set. So, when you and I interact with Google AI overview, or even more so Google\'s AI mode, when I'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt it and ask a question, it will go and browse the web to inform its answer. And it can in some cases look at 400, 500 different domains. Far more than you and I, even you, Toby, with the amount'

[07:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of tabs that you have open. You can open a tab on your own mode. So, that already gives you a hint about the optimization approach. An element of it is strategic. You are already part of someone else\'s training set. Every asset'

[07:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you have published over the lifespan of your brand is encoded and understood and referenced inside these models. But also, you\'re part of that topical'

[07:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'window. What happens when they go out and look for new and relevant information to ensure they give you the best answer. So, between those two levers of optimization, part of it lands in the brand wealth because in that case it\'s'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not just the SEO team\'s responsibility. You may build a brilliant website that can be indexed and accessed and understood by AI agents. But if your Super Bowl campaign is talking about'

[07:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something completely different and it lives on YouTube and becomes part of someone else\'s training set, there\'s some cognitive dissonance there for an AI model. Similarly then in our case, if you are purely a brand marketer, you know what your brand can stand for. But every'

[08:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'marketer knows that doesn\'t mean everyone on your team is sticking to the same brief and creating consistent memorable assets. &gt;&gt; Right. And and I mean, you even before we started the'

