VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very well is one, respect for the model. You don\'t really think you\'re going to outwit something that effectively is, you know, superintelligence. It\'s on par if not at least different to humans. Video is the most effective medium'

[17:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'around how to train a model. And this is a really interesting insight around video from the model\'s point of view. We looked at AI recommendations that represent around a trillion dollars of consumer spending. So across our three'

[18:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'biggest markets, every major model, every major category, the sum total of a good chunk of the world\'s economy. The only platform that appeared across every single AI model and every single category was YouTube.'

[18:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And when we drilled into what YouTube content was being surfaced, the average video was 11 minutes long. It looked probably something similar to this. A group of people who are passionate about a product, often streaming or recording a clip in their'

[18:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bedroom, their bathroom, or their office about why they cared so much about a product. Some of these videos even had spreadsheets in the background. But the thing that united them was that'

[18:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they were passionate, expert, and authoritative people. And models were learning from their content about which brands to recommend. So I keep on come back to that term of respect. Respect the model cuz it\'s'

[19:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to pretty quickly realize you\'re trying to trick it. And respect the people who talk about your brand. The people who are willing to be a part of that story. Because models increasingly learn a lot more from attending a video'

[19:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or on a passionate advocate or someone simply explaining a difference than a really polished webpage or a blog post with a bunch of stats that we all know are inflated. &gt;&gt; I I I I love the idea actually of um the'

[19:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'incentive being towards substance. That\'s that\'s got to be a fantastic thing for content and what we\'re confronted with online in general. Um so that that that\'s that\'s that\'s quite reassuring to hear frankly.'

[19:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Um so I\'m glad to hear it. &gt;&gt; This is the the wonderful nature of this way. Every conversation we have with a client follows a similar arc. The first half is oh my god, this is a fundamental change with frankly inhuman intelligence.'

